

Objective

Configure a Group Policy Object (GPO) to prevent users from running executable (.exe) files from their Downloads folder using Software Restriction Policies (SRP).

Lab Environment
	•	Windows Server 2022 (Domain Controller)
	•	Windows 10 Domain-Joined Client
	•	Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS)
	•	Group Policy Management (GPMC)

Steps Performed
	•	Created a new GPO named SOFTWARE RESTRICTION POLICY.
	•	Linked the GPO to the appropriate Organizational Unit (OU).
	•	Created Software Restriction Policies under:
	•	Computer Configuration → Policies → Windows Settings → Security Settings → Software Restriction Policies
	•	Configured Enforcement:
	•	Apply to all software files
	•	Apply to all users except local administrators
	•	Ignore certificate rules
	•	Created a Path Rule:
	•	Path: %USERPROFILE%\Downloads\*.exe
	•	Security Level: Disallowed
	•	Updated Group Policy using:

CMD:gpupdate /force

•	Verified that executable files placed inside the Downloads folder could no longer run.

Troubleshooting

During testing, the policy did not work because the path rule contained a typo Incorrect: %USERPROFILE%\Downoads\*.exe
I corrected it to %USERPROFILE%\Downloads\*.exe
After correcting the path and running gpupdate /force, the restriction worked successfully.

Key Learning Points
	•	Software Restriction Policies use exact path matching.
	•	Even a small typo can prevent a policy from working.
	•	Computer Configuration policies apply to all users who log on to the affected computer.
	•	Changes to Group Policy require a policy refresh or restart before taking effect.
	•	Disabling a GPO prevents Windows from processing any settings contained within it.

